{
    "id": "tokio_rs_tokio_7417",
    "repo_name": "tokio-rs/tokio",
    "repo_url": "https://github.com/tokio-rs/tokio",
    "base_commit": "69290a64327a017fd9a0cedefaac60c4993c3b54",
    "pr_number": 7417,
    "issue_number": 7411,
    "issue_title": "runtime hooks: expose spawn caller location in `on_task_spawn` hook",
    "issue_body": "**Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.**\n\nI'm using Tokio's unstable runtime hooks to integrate with an external diagnostics/observability system (DTrace). The function passed to [`runtime::Builder::on_task_spawn`](https://docs.rs/tokio/latest/tokio/runtime/struct.Builder.html#method.on_task_spawn) method is called with a `runtime::TaskMeta` type that contains the `task::Id` assigned by the runtime to that task. The task ID can be used to correlate the `on_before_task_poll`, `on_after_task_poll`, and `on_task_terminate` runtime hooks with when the task was spawned.\n\nHowever, there isn't an easy way to determine _which_ task in the program's source code is being spawned. The runtime hooks can be used to track various events such as polls over the entire lifetime of the task, but there isn't an easy way to determine what those tasks *are*, limiting its use for debugging and profiling purposes.\n\n**Describe the solution you'd like**\n\nAll of the functions involved in task spawning are annotated with the `#[track_caller]` attribute. This means that, within the call chain of `tokio::spawn` and similar APIs, `std::panic::Location::caller()` will return the source location in the *user's code* where the task was spawned, which basically tells you what it is and lets you associate task IDs with application source code. This is currently used by the `tokio_unstable` tracing events. However, it's not exposed to the `on_task_spawn` runtime hook. I'd like it to be passed to that hook.\n\nThere are a few different API designs for this, which have different tradeoffs around breaking changes and API niceness.\n\nOne option is to add the `std::panic::Location` to the `runtime::TaskMeta` struct. The advantage of this is that it doesn't change the signature of the `on_task_spawn` function, so no code currently using the runtime hooks will break. On the other hand, the spawn location is only cheaply available when the task is spawned, so this wouldn't be present in the `TaskMeta` passed to the `on_before_task_poll`, `on_after_task_poll`, and `on_task_terminate` hook functions. This means we'd have a `fn spawn_location(&self) -> Option<&std::panic::Location>` method on `TaskMeta` that would always be `Some` in `on_task_spawn` and `None` in the other hooks, and the user would have to `unwrap()` it in `on_task_spawn`. This is a bit unfortunate.\n\nOn the other hand, we could change the signature of `on_task_spawn` to include the spawn location as a separate argument, like `fn on_task_spawn(meta: &TaskMeta<'_>, spawn_location: &'static std::panic::Location)`. This would break existing code that uses the runtime hooks, since we're changing the signature of the function. However, the runtime hooks are unstable precisely *because* we want to reserve the ability to break them, but it could cause some annoyance for code that currently uses them. The benefit is that we have a much nicer API for the hook functions, where the additional data that's only provided to `on_task_spawn` is just only passed to that function.\n\nFinally, we could add a _new_ hook function like `on_task_spawn_with_location` that takes both the `TaskMeta` and the spawn location as arguments. This way, existing uses of the `on_task_spawn` hook function would still compile, but we don't have an `Option` value in the task meta that the user has to handle the presence/lack of depending on which hook they are in. The downside of this is that now there's two different hook APIs for spawns, which is kinda unfortunate.\n\nReally, it's a question of how eager we are to break existing uses of the `on_task_spawn` hook. It requires the unstable features, so we _can_ break it freely, but it would still cause broken builds for existing uses, so we may want to avoid that if possible. Any of these approaches would solve the problem, depending on which API design tradeoffs we're more comfortable with.\n\n**Describe alternatives you've considered**\n\nI also considered a few alternative ways of solving this problem, which have their own flaws. \n\nFor one thing, a DTrace probe in `on_task_spawn` can capture the callstack, which does let us see where in the program the task is being spawned from. But, it's not as nice, as there's a lot of additional stack frames that aren't actually relevant for the problem of just identifying where the task is spawned. Also (and this is specific to DTrace), the way the stack trace can be used in a D script is somewhat more limiting than a string or something that's passed as an argument to the probe. The caller location is a much better answer for the specific question of\"what the task is in the source code\".\n\nAnother approach I looked into is just adding the `#[track_caller]` attribute to the callback function passed to `on_task_spawn`, and making sure it's also present on the entire call chain between `tokio::spawn` and where the runtime calls `TaskHooks::spawn`. This would be nice, as it doesn't have downsides of breaking the unstable API *or* making the API less pleasant to use --- the `on_task_spawn` callback can just do `std::panic::Location::caller()` on its own if it wants to. Unfortunately, this doesn't work, as the hook callback is internally represented as an `Arc<dyn Fn(&TaskMeta<'_>) + Send + Sync>`, rather than a `fn` pointer. Since it's called through a `dyn Fn`, the caller location is always in libcore's `function.rs`, instead:\n```rust\nLocation { file: \"/home/eliza/.rustup/toolchains/stable-x86_64-unknown-linux-gnu/lib/rustlib/src/rust/library/core/src/ops/function.rs\", line: 79, col: 5 }\n```\nUnfortunately, there's no real way to fix that, due to the dynamic dispatch.\n\n**Additional context**\n\nI'm happy to open a PR implementing this, but I wanted to first ask which API design is preferable.\n",
